üéØ Key Findings

  • Classification approach wins: Achieved highest F1-score (0.284) with excellent recall (97.5%)

üîç Methodology Evolution

Figure 2: Evolution of methodology and performance throughout the study

üêõ Critical Issues Discovered

‚ùå Data Leakage Issues

  • Multiple samples per R-peak
  • Overlapping windows in train/validation
  • Threshold optimization on validation set
  • Artificially balanced datasets

‚úÖ Corrections Applied

  • One sample per R-peak only
  • Time-based splitting
  • Separate holdout for threshold optimization
  • Realistic class imbalance maintained

üß† Architectural Approaches

1. Classification Approach (Winner)

Architecture: Multi-scale CNN with residual connections Input: 63-sample windows (0.5s) of EEG Output: Binary classification (R-peak vs No R-peak) Training: Focal loss with optimal threshold finding

2. U-Net Sequence-to-Sequence

Architecture: Encoder-decoder with skip connections Input: 250-sample segments (2.0s) of EEG Output: Continuous R-peak probability signal Training: MSE loss against Gaussian peak targets

3. Ultimate Enhancement (Attempted)

Architecture: Advanced CNN with attention mechanisms Features: Multi-scale blocks, channel attention, data augmentation Training: Dynamic focal loss with advanced scheduling

üéØ Clinical Relevance

High Recall Priority: The classification model's 97.5% recall means it rarely misses heartbeats, which is crucial for cardiac monitoring applications. The 16.7% precision indicates some false positives, but these can be filtered in post-processing.

üî¨ Technical Implementation

Signal Processing Pipeline

  1. Data Loading: OpenBCI EXG format (ECG + EEG channels)
  2. Filtering: 60Hz notch filter + 0.5-40Hz bandpass
  3. R-peak Detection: NeuroKit2 on ECG for ground truth
  4. Downsampling: 250Hz ‚Üí 125Hz with R-peak preservation
  5. Normalization: StandardScaler/RobustScaler

Data Characteristics

  • Total samples: 242,513 at 125Hz (~32 minutes)
  • R-peaks found: 1,894 heartbeats
  • Natural imbalance: ~0.8% positive samples
  • Realistic challenge: Cross-modal signal prediction

üí° Key Insights

üèÜ What Worked Best

  • Time-based splitting: Maintains chronological order for realistic evaluation
  • One-to-one matching: Prevents double-counting in evaluation
  • Physiological constraints: Minimum R-R intervals for realistic detection
  • Focal loss: Handles class imbalance effectively

‚ö†Ô∏è Lessons Learned

  • Code review crucial: ChatGPT's analysis caught critical bugs
  • Evaluation methodology: Proper validation prevents inflated results
  • Simpler often better: Basic CNN outperformed complex architectures
  • Domain constraints: Physiological limits improve performance

üöÄ Future Recommendations

Immediate Improvements

  • Multi-lead EEG: Use multiple EEG channels for better signal quality
  • Subject-specific training: Personalized models for individual physiology
  • Real-time processing: Optimize for continuous monitoring applications
  • Hybrid approaches: Combine EEG with other modalities (PPG, accelerometer)

Advanced Research Directions

  • Transformer architectures: Self-attention for long-range temporal dependencies
  • Meta-learning: Quick adaptation to new subjects with few samples
  • Uncertainty quantification: Confidence estimates for predictions
  • Adversarial training: Robustness to signal artifacts and noise
